explanation:
To determine whether OS_DeleteAllObjects (directly or indirectly) uses memcmp to compare null-terminated strings you must inspect the functions it calls and the callbacks it passes. Reasons for each symbol:

- OS_ForEachObjectOfType: Direct callee used to iterate and select objects; it may perform name/type comparisons internally (possibly using memcmp).
- OS_ForEachObject: Direct callee that iterates over all object types; same rationale as above for potential string comparisons.
- OS_CleanUpObject: The callback passed into the iterator calls. It may compare object names or string fields using memcmp; must be checked.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorInit: Part of the iteration implementation called by OS_ForEachObjectOfType; may set up name matching or other comparisons.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorProcessEntry: Core iterator routine that examines each entry; likely place where name/identifier comparisons occur and where memcmp might be used.
- OS_ObjectIdIteratorDestroy: Iterator teardown; included to allow full inspection of iterator behavior (completeness of analysis).
- OS_TaskDelay: Direct callee; included to check whether any test or stub path invoked by delay uses memcmp (through its impl or stubs).
- OS_TaskDelay_Impl: Implementation of TaskDelay; inspect for any string comparisons used in delay handling or debugging paths.
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: Appears in the static graph for several callees and test stubs; mock/test handlers can perform argument matching using memcmp.
- UT_GetStubEntry: Part of the UT handler chain; may contain comparison logic used by stubs.
- UT_SetHandlerFunction: Part of UT harness; may compare strings (handler names) when selecting handlers.
- UT_DefaultStubImpl: Default stub implementation used by many APIs; could implement argument matching or debug prints that use memcmp.
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData: Registered by iterator/stub paths in the graph; may contain comparison logic in metadata handling.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType / UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: UT stub support functions that might inspect or compare string-based return/context data.

Inspecting the listed symbols (their source code) is necessary to conclusively determine whether any path reachable from OS_DeleteAllObjects uses memcmp to compare null-terminated strings. Only after checking these functions (and in particular OS_CleanUpObject and the iterator/process-entry code) can you rule in or out a MISRA C memcmp violation.
